Rule: Analytics SaaS Production Backend Standards (NestJS)

Purpose:

Maintain a clean, scalable, observable, multi-tenant analytics SaaS backend.  
Prevent architectural drift, data corruption, security leaks, and metric instability.

Scope:

This rule applies to the **NestJS analytics backend** only. It does not replace frontend (Next.js `app/`) or shared UI rules.

Maturity:

Meet this standard **before production**. Early phases may temporarily simplify (for example schema registry depth, metric definition ceremony, or coverage targets) **only** when the gap is documented in the module README or PR and has a tracked follow-up to full compliance.

Core principles:

Clarity over cleverness
Consistency over speed
Separation over convenience
Data safety over shortcuts
Observability over assumptions


------------------------------------------------

ARCHITECTURE LAYERS

System must follow:

Controller → Service → Repository → Database

Workers operate outside request flow.

Controllers:

Handle HTTP only.
Validate input.
Call services.
Return responses.

Controllers must not:

Contain business logic
Access repositories directly
Execute SQL
Call workers directly

Controllers may:

Call services that trigger jobs.


------------------------------------------------

MODULE DESIGN

Modules must be domain driven.

Core modules:

auth
users
workspaces
datasources
events
metrics
dashboards
api-keys
alerts
billing

Shared modules:

config
database
logger
guards
decorators

Rules:

Modules communicate through exported services only.
Avoid circular dependencies.

Preferred dependency flow:

workspaces → events → metrics → dashboards

Exceptions allowed if documented.


------------------------------------------------

MULTI TENANCY RULES

All business data belongs to a workspace.

Required fields:

id
workspaceId
createdAt
updatedAt

Queries must filter by workspace unless:

System admin context
Internal workers
Migration scripts

Workspace bypass must always be explicit.


------------------------------------------------

EVENT SYSTEM RULES

Events are immutable history.

Allowed:

Insert events.

Forbidden:

Updating events
Deleting events outside retention policies

Events must include:

workspaceId
eventName
timestamp
sourceId

Events must support deduplication using:

eventId
idempotencyKey
hash

System must accept late arriving data.

Never rely on insertion order.

Always rely on event timestamp.


------------------------------------------------

EVENT SCHEMA CONTRACT RULES

Event schemas are permanent contracts once used.

Events must define:

eventName
description
required properties
optional properties
property types

Rules:

Never change meaning of properties.
Never change property types.
Never reuse property names.

Allowed:

Adding optional fields.
Adding new events.

Forbidden:

Removing required properties.
Changing types.
Renaming properties without transition.

Breaking changes require:

New event version.
New event name.

Example:

user_signup
user_signup_v2

Event validation required.

Invalid events must:

Be rejected
Or stored separately

Schema registry recommended:

events/schema/

Purpose:

Prevent silent metric corruption.


------------------------------------------------

DATA PROCESSING RULES

Metrics must be precomputed.

Correct flow:

events → workers → aggregations → metrics tables

Never compute heavy metrics in request path.

Reason:

Protect API latency.


------------------------------------------------

METRIC DEFINITION RULES

Metrics must be explicitly defined.

Metric definitions must include:

Name
Description
SQL definition
Data source
Refresh frequency
Owner

Metrics must be reproducible.

Metric calculations must:

Use aggregation tables
Not raw event scans

Metric changes must be versioned.

Never silently change metric formulas.


------------------------------------------------

BACKGROUND JOB RULES

Workers handle:

Aggregation
Connector sync
Forecasting
Backfills
Large imports

Workers must be:

Retry safe
Idempotent
Observable

Workers must track:

Start time
End time
Retry attempts
Failure cause

Workers must never block API requests.


------------------------------------------------

DATA BACKFILL RULES

Backfills must be safe.

Rules:

Backfills must run as jobs.
Backfills must be resumable.
Backfills must not block ingestion.

Backfills must:

Track progress
Support restart
Log impact

Never:

Lock event tables
Block production traffic

Always:

Batch operations.


------------------------------------------------

TRANSACTION RULES

Use transactions when:

Updating multiple related tables
Billing updates
Subscription changes
Credit accounting

Avoid transactions for:

Event ingestion
Logging
Simple inserts

Rules:

Keep short.
Never call external APIs inside transactions.


------------------------------------------------

DATABASE RULES

Schema changes require migrations.

Rules:

Forward only migrations.
Never modify applied migrations.
Must be idempotent.

Breaking schema change process:

Add new column
Migrate data
Switch code
Remove old column later

Zero downtime rule:

Deploy compatible code first.

Event tables must index:

workspaceId
timestamp
eventName


------------------------------------------------

API DESIGN RULES

All endpoints must:

Use DTO validation
Use proper HTTP codes
Return consistent format

Success:

{
  success: true,
  data: {}
}

Error:

{
  success: false,
  error: "",
  message: ""
}


------------------------------------------------

API CONTRACT RULES

API contracts are permanent once released.

Breaking changes require:

New version
Migration guide
Deprecation notice
Transition window

Breaking changes include:

Removing fields
Renaming fields
Changing types
Changing response structure
Changing auth behavior

Allowed changes:

Adding optional fields
Adding endpoints
Expanding enums
Relaxing validation

Never:

Remove required fields in same version.
Change response shape silently.
Change error formats without versioning.

Consistency rules:

Same error structure.
Same pagination structure.
Same naming patterns.

Responses must remain deterministic.


------------------------------------------------

API VERSIONING RULES

Version pattern:

/v1/events
/v1/metrics

Rules:

Support minimum 12 months.
6 month deprecation notice.

Never:

Change behavior silently.

Always:

Create new version.


------------------------------------------------

RATE LIMITING RULES

Protect all public APIs.

Apply limits to:

Auth endpoints
Event ingestion
Public APIs

Limits must support:

IP
API key
Workspace

System must:

Return 429
Fail gracefully
Never crash


------------------------------------------------

SECURITY RULES

Authentication:

JWT expiration required.
Refresh tokens required.
Token rotation required.

Authorization:

RBAC required.
Permissions checked in service layer.

Never trust:

workspaceId from client
roles from frontend

Always verify server side.

Data protection:

Encrypt:

API keys
Tokens
Credentials

Never log:

Passwords
Tokens
Payment data
PII

Database safety:

Parameterized queries only.

Never build SQL strings.

Secrets:

Environment or secret manager only.

Never commit secrets.


------------------------------------------------

IDEMPOTENCY RULES

Operations must be retry safe.

Required for:

Event ingestion
Webhooks
Billing updates
Workers

Strategies:

Idempotency keys
Unique constraints
Deduplication

Workers must assume retries.


------------------------------------------------

ERROR HANDLING RULES

Use structured errors.

Types:

Validation
Domain
Infrastructure

Domain error examples:

InsufficientCreditsError
InvalidWorkspaceStateError

Never expose stack traces.


------------------------------------------------

LOGGING RULES

Use structured logging.

Log:

Errors
Job failures
Security events
Connector failures

Never log:

Secrets
Tokens
Credentials
PII


------------------------------------------------

OBSERVABILITY RULES

System must be measurable.

Expose:

GET /health
GET /health/ready
GET /health/live

Track:

Latency
Error rates
Queue backlog
Job duration
DB query time

Critical logs must include:

workspaceId
requestId
correlationId
operation
duration

Never deploy blind systems.


------------------------------------------------

PERFORMANCE RULES

Never load large datasets into memory.

Always use:

SQL aggregation
Indexes
Pagination
Precomputation

Bad:

Load 1M rows into JS.

Good:

Aggregate in database.


------------------------------------------------

TESTING RULES

Coverage targets:

Auth:
90%

Event ingestion:
90%

Billing:
90%

Metrics:
85%

Core services:
80%

Required tests:

Unit:

Services
Validators

Integration:

Repositories
APIs

E2E:

Auth flow
Event ingestion
Metrics flow

Critical modules must not merge without tests.


------------------------------------------------

DOCUMENTATION RULES

APIs must include:

Swagger docs
Examples
Error cases

Modules must include README:

Purpose
Responsibilities
Dependencies

Complex logic must explain why.

Architecture decisions must be documented when changing:

Data flow
Pipelines
Tenancy model


------------------------------------------------

CONNECTOR RELIABILITY RULES

External connectors must assume failure.

Required:

Retries with backoff
Timeout protection
Partial sync handling

Connectors must track:

Last sync time
Sync status
Failure reason

Never assume external APIs are reliable.


------------------------------------------------

FEATURE ADDITION RULE

New features must include:

Module
Service
DTO
Entity
Controller
Tests
Documentation

Never place logic in unrelated modules.


------------------------------------------------


------------------------------------------------

COST CONTROL RULES

System must prevent unbounded resource usage.

All expensive operations must have limits.

DATABASE QUERY LIMITS

Queries must enforce:

Default row limits (max 10,000 unless justified)
Query timeout (default 30 seconds)
Pagination for large datasets

Complex queries must:

Use EXPLAIN before approval
Avoid full table scans unless indexed
Require review if scanning large event tables

Forbidden:

Unbounded SELECT queries
Queries without workspace filters
Queries without limits on event tables


EVENT INGESTION LIMITS

Ingestion must enforce:

Maximum batch size
Maximum request payload size
Maximum events per request
Rate limits per workspace

System must reject:

Oversized batches
Malformed payloads
Abnormally large property objects

System must monitor:

Events per workspace
Storage growth rate
Ingestion spikes


QUERY PERFORMANCE CONTROL

New complex queries must:

Include explain plan review
Verify index usage
Avoid cross joins on large tables

Query complexity scoring recommended using:

Estimated rows
Join count
Aggregation cost

High cost queries must:

Require optimization
Use pre-aggregations
Use caching where possible


COST ATTRIBUTION RULES

System must track cost drivers per workspace:

Storage usage
Event volume
Query compute usage
Connector sync usage
Data export volume

System must support:

Workspace usage tracking
Cost anomaly alerts
Internal cost reporting

Recommended:

Expose usage metrics to customers.

Examples:

Event volume usage
Storage consumption
API usage

Purpose:

Prevent hidden cost growth.
Enable usage-based pricing.
Protect platform sustainability.

------------------------------------------------

FINAL OPERATING STANDARD

System must always remain:

Modular
Observable
Tenant safe
Secure
Tested
Predictable
Extendable
Recoverable

If a feature reduces clarity or safety,
it must be redesigned before merging.